Find a dispensary that has a medical side and ask about cannabinoids. Like I said, CBN is great for sleep, CBG is great for nausea/ stomach issues and anxiety. Edibles aren’t “scary” if you know what you’re eating.

My girlfriend and I ate a ‘medical grade’ edible for the first time last week, it was a gummy from a well known reputable brand in my area, the person who gave it to us (my new neighbor) told us that the dosage was around 300mg, which, being a seasoned smoker, i knew couldn’t have been true and my girlfriend and I ate both of ours in their entirety, i actually like to let mine dissolve under my tongue because back in my not so good days of dabbling with different prescription pills, that was one assumed way to create a quicker onset.

Fast forward we go back home and i still don’t feel any different, i’d been managing some health concerns that turned out to not be anything serious however i suffer from OCD which causes me to hyper focus on things like my pulse, and other usually very minor bodily sensations that the majority of people recognize and superficial or insignificant.

Shortly afterwards it hit me, not like a 300mg would (i suspect it was actually 30mg, but there were other family members of mine who also ate the same edible who saw the packaging that read 300mg) but i remember feeling like i was floating on air whenever i was walking, my thoughts would go everywhere, and my girlfriend an i would get sudden bouts of laughter and hyperactivity.

When we all started to wind down for the night that’s when the real power of it hit me, i laid in bed and became hyper vigilant of my body and i began thinking back to my recent medical scares, it had me second guessing what numerous doctors have told me was fine.

In the end, i got really tired and just ended up crashing soon thereafter, ur i will say it can be a very positive experience as long you don’t allow the intensity of the feelings or thoughts you may have consume you completely.

Again, i’m a season smoker of marijuana, so having experience under my belt certainly helps when i get that infamous uneasy feeling that weed can cause, for some people it’s just not a good drug to indulge in, but it’s certainly mind over matter.

If you ever find yourself in an uncomfortable state of highness, a common tactic that i use is repeating things in my head like “You just smoked a few minutes ago, you’re high.” or, in extreme panic situations i remind myself or someone else “NO ONE has ever died from weed, smoked or eaten, you will not be patient zero”

We had about 20 (or so) grams on paper plates, just breaking it up for almost an hour. It turned into a giant heaping mound. Since he lived with his parents, we had to also make a regular brownie batch. This left very little brownie mix for the “brownies” we had set out to bake. Needless to say, we had no idea what we were doing. We put all the weed into the smaller pie tray (about 6 inch diameter) and it was about 1 inch tall. I ate a piece, and it didn’t taste like a brownie at all. After about 20 mins, I ate another piece. I was very disappointed. It wasn’t working, and we’d seemingly come this far for nothing. I ate a third piece (more than half the pie now) and yet still- nothing. We decided we were gonna just smoke a blunt instead. I took one hit, and BAM!! I was on another planet. The cotton mouth alone was inexplicable. Three seconds after I’d swallowed the water, my tongue already felt like an iguana’s back. I was high as hell for about 6 or 7 hours, watched Super Troopers, went to sleep, and woke up the NEXT day higher than any weed had ever gotten me before. The main point of this story is that you simply cannot overdose on weed. If you could, I’d be a goner.

I remember one time when I had my cousin over, I was really bored; when I remembered the weed edibles my grandma had prepared and left frozen in the freezer in the back shed. Considering it was night time and I didn't want my cousin to smell any weed smoke on me, I just imagined eating it would be the socially-safer alternative. I was dead wrong. I had never previously tried psychedelics before this experience, but I swear it was just like one. I ate the weed edible out of the fridge really quickly as to not be seen eating it; and out of naivety, I ate the whole brownie. Empty stomach and all, I know. Afterwards, I headed back inside to watch TV with my cousin, who was probably just as bored as I was. Well, I was no longer bored anymore, as I knew I was going to be feeling something; although I wasn't expecting it to be that intense. 30 minutes pass, which is the time I read up on the internet that it was supposed to start kicking in. I didn't feel anything. Irritated, and thinking that it wasn't going to do anything to me, I almost considered going out and eating a second. Thank god I didn't do that... I would probably be unable to move.

Anyway, I sit for another 5 minutes or so, and begin zoning out far more than normal I notice. Nothing still felt wrong with me just sitting down, beside that of-course, so I began to stand up to get some water. However, as I am standing up, time all of a sudden feels like it has come to a standstill. My arms move visibly very slowly in front of me, and immediate panic sets in. I legitimately felt like I was in slow motion, and I had never experienced this ever before so I became overwhelmed with how restricted my movement felt. Trying to seem as normal as possible to my cousin, I slow-motion walk over to the sink where I get a glass of water and chug it all down. The chlorine in the water, as I remember, tasted terrible. It was as if my taste was enhanced by 100x. Afterwards, I sat back down again. Next, my worst nightmare had started whilst under the influence. My cousin was conversing with me. I couldn't understand anything he was saying, as I kept zoning out mid-speech; and the fact that he sounded like he was speaking in slow motion. I mindlessly agreed with whatever he was talking about over and over again. I could hear the slowness in my voice, and became concerned that he'd know something was up; as I was not supposed to be eating edibles at that age. Time slowly passes with me in a terrifying dream-like state where I keep imagining myself floating outside of my own body, and flying away through the universe at the speed of light. I even remember feeling the acceleration of that hallucination. As a first-timer to psychedelic experiences, I was quite literally freaking out on the verge of going insane.

Eventually, I couldn't take it anymore, and I turned off the TV, stating in my slowed voice "I'm getting tired" to my cousin. He nods and says something incomprehensible, and I grab one final glass of water before lying down in bed. Of-course, I wasn't tired. My entire body was energetic with the adrenaline pumping through my veins, after all. I just wanted to force myself to go to sleep so I could end this experience already. Big mistake. As I am lying down, I begin to REALLY zone out. I almost felt like I was in a weird lucid dream-like state, except it felt far different to a dream. I kept imagining this new dimension where everything felt unexplainably alien. The best way I can describe it to this day is it was like the fourth dimension. My vision and my entire consciousness was just one side of a square, and the other sides were stuff that, post edible, I CANNOT explain no matter how hard I try. It really messes with my brain thinking about it, and I can't even comprehend it that well anymore. As I was having these weird experiences with what I perceived to be another dimension, I was also experiencing a no-gravity state. I felt like I was just a weird consciousness floating around through the plane of the universe. I also had closed-eye visuals that I can only describe as alien, as they were coloured orange and green, all over the middle of my vision. After a while, I feel deathly ill and throw up in the sink and pace around for a while, freaking out. My cousin could obviously hear me pacing around, I thought to myself, and he must've thought I was insane; so I got back in bed, and surprisingly, after more weird out-of-body experiences I can't really remember, I drift off and wake up the next morning feeling drained and tired.

Moral of the story? Don't just eat whole edibles when bored, especially without realising what it as in store for you, like I did. It was by far one of the most unpleasant experiences I've had in my life. LSD was way better in terms of me preserving my sanity, although I did get to the point in my LSD trip where I hugged the toilet and considered it my saviour against a bad trip, so I guess not entirely.

Recently I decided to take a 250mg edible with a buddy of mine. They were called “Stoneo’s”, looked exactly like an oreo, and even tasted like oreo.

Just for context, both of us are regular THC consumers, and at the time we believed 250mg would be nothing. Very wrong is what were.

After eating the Stoneo, the first and second hours were pretty relaxing; we were playing guitar, chatting about the day, and what we were anticipating with the come-up. Not too much happened here except for acquiring the munchies.

Hour three or so in, and things started to get funny. In my general peripheral view there was Hulu on the TV, the munchies on the coffee table, and my buddy next to me. The TV started wiggling slightly then got a little bit fuzzy, so I got up to wash my face and check if I was dreaming. The second I looked at myself in the mirror, I knew I was in trouble. My face was pale, and my cheeks were turning red. I went back to the couch, and the visuals started to fizzle out.

Hour four and five in, and it wasn’t getting easier. I had music playing on subs in my room, and I was sitting on the edge of my bed. My buddy was across the room by the door, completely submerged in the music. I was sitting there, literally just staring at my phone. I had no clue what it was or what I was doing, and I just let it slide out of my hand; I remember putting on Sober to Death by Car Seat Headrest, knowing nothing of my existence or why I was in my room. I just fell back, and stared at my ceiling. The white wall felt like an empty void, calling me like a hero called to action. This only felt like the beginning.

Hours six and seven came through, and it surprisingly turned out to be the bitter-sweet comedown. Still passed out on my bed, I was sitting upright with a pillow in my hand. I had kept fading in and out of consciousness, disconnecting and reconnecting with the world. At one point I heard one of my cats meow, and it snapped me out of the in-and-out tripping I was going through. My cat came up to me and nudged me, and it almost felt like a rekindled relationship between pet and owner. I hugged the shit out of him and continued to pet him for what felt like forever; it felt like I hadn’t seen my cat in decades, and that he’d been lost alone this whole time. While all of this was going on, my buddy was still passed out on the other end of the room, this time on his side. I knew he was fine so I simply left him alone.

Hour eight came, and it was definitely time for bed. I got up for what felt like the first time in forever, and poked my buddy. He flailed and his pupils were all disoriented and undilated. He panicked and couldn’t sit upright for a fee minutes, but he caught track of himself. The both of us got up and checked back in with ourselves and reality, and we called it a night after storytelling for a solid half-hour.

The following day felt surreal. It was almost as if I had come back from being in a VR experience. The feelings I had and the memories I made while seeing what I saw all felt so tangible, yet at the exact same time so fake. It took me at least a few hours to re-connect with everything and everybody the following day, and it was even difficult to keep a basic focus throughout the day.

Long story short the 25g was both a living hell and a beautifully heavenly experience; if you’re interested in taking a 250mg or more dose, you should definitely do your research ahead of time and mentally prepare. It’s something that not everyone can mentally handle. To all of you, stay safe out there and happy consuming!

One time my boyfriend and I got edibles; a cookie and a Rice Krispie treat. We ate them at 4pm and waited around for them to kick in. 5pm rolls around and I start feeling it. I’m feel relaxed, music sounds better, and I’m having a good time. 30 minutes later I was the highest I’d ever been in my whole life. I was thinking in SHAPES, triangles to be exact. I forgot the English language as a whole and invented a whole other language so I could communicate with the outside world. My whole brain lit up all at once and I thought every single thought I had ever thought in my whole life. I couldn’t stop picturing random things in my head. My heart was pounding so fast I was CONVINCED I was having a heart attack and told my boyfriend to call 911. I tried to convince him that the high “wasn’t normal” and that the edibles had been mixed with BATH SALTS OR ACID. I was shaking uncontrollably and couldn’t handle any sounds or even my own voice. I was really convinced I would never returned to reality and cried to my boyfriend about how I was going to die and told him my goodbyes. 3 hours later I fell asleep and woke up the next day still high. After the high ended I felt incredible. It was like it rewired my brain. No more anxiety, no more bad thoughts, just peace and happiness. I love and HATE weed.

1) The high from eating marijuana does NOT last "4-8 hours" like you make it sound. The high is just as long but with a more stretched out onset and comedown, making i appear longer to those who don't consume cannabis frequently. Ask any heavy cannabis user or anyone who works in the industry, it's no less an urban legend than saying "You can take a tab of LSD and never stop tripping".
2) While yes, there is evidence that 11-OH-THC has been produce through metabolizing process and yes, this is technically a stronger molecule than Delta-9-THC, it is by no means some magic or incredible way to potentiate your weed like you make it sound. The high - compared to smoking - is just much more body oriented generally. To clarify some strains are proven to produce more energetic behavior and/or mood when smoked or vaporized but this is something that's not attributed to edibles very often. In short, it's just a stronger body high. That is it. I can't speak for you, but personally I've almost always found the same people who claim edibles give you this just absolutely crazy strong high, more than not are the same type of people to hardly even smoke (or consume) that much in to begin with.
3) We both know there are zero cases where smoking marijuana was a definitive cause of a tumor. Stop it.
4) One thing I've will note is I have consistently seen edibles far more unregulated along the west coast than any other product. Some people I've done business with in the past have no problem telling you "Yeah we market our cookies as 250mg but really there 450mg". That's still not an absurd amount, I know, but it's the point that it's very plausible lots of people out there are being misinformed. (Why some people would do that is beyond me, everyone seemed to have their own reason - from legality to shits and giggles. It hardly makes sense to me.)

Weed gets you stoned AF but edibles make you high.

High gets you the same mental effects but drasticly reduces the "Body high" as ive heard people call it.

The edibles give, me personally, way less of an effect then smoking it.
I kept in mind that smoking works faster due to the shorter track it takes to get to the brain but even when you spread this out over a longer period with a vaporiser only taking a puff or 2 every 15 minutes it still makes a huge difference in overal experience.

Might be becouse im used to smoking it which trains the brain to be more sensitive to this portion then the other.
(placebo effect probably playing quite the role here).

Story time...

So I have a friend who is incredible at making pot brownies. She somehow is able to make them very strong, while damn near eliminating the taste of the weed itself... so if you didn't know that her brownies were pot brownies... well... they would largely taste like your average chocolate chip brownie... any off taste you might detect is small enough to be ignored.

First time I ever had them (*years* ago), I was at a party. I honestly didn't know they were pot brownies. I saw people eating them, so I ate one. I also then shared a Volcano bag with a couple other people. Getting the munchies about 45 minutes later, I decided to have a second one. I saw that the people who ate the brownies were eating what looked to me like new pieces, so I grabbed a second one.

I finished the second one, then hit a bong, rolled a blunt I had myself, shared a Pax, and had some coca cola spiked with green dragon. At the same time, someone had done a Panda Express run, and I gave them some money to get me some (okay... a lot of) orange chicken.

I started to feel sick, and was finally told that the brownies were pot brownies, and that everyone who had a brownie was still working on their first when I went back for my second.

I spent the rest of that night, and well into the morning, with my head planted firmly over a toilet bowl. (Please note that I had zero alcohol or any other drug that entire evening.)

For some reason, this experience put me off specifically edibles and bongs, while I'm quite good with green dragon and vapes (I don't smoke anymore). The smell of bongs make me nauseous, and I'm kind of afraid of edibles (still).

Real quick fact check... There is no way to "legalize" anything. You can simply decriminalize something by removing laws that make it illegal. But also Laws are cumulative. You don't abide by the laws of whoever has the most relevant jurisdiction, you must abide by all jurisdictions in an area. So where I live in Marietta, Georgia, for example, I must abide by local law, county law, state law and federal. Usually these are overlapping. But cover different things. My city and county both have laws about traffic, because they enforce traffic laws, whereas State and Federal tend to not make laws they can't enforce. That said, the decriminalization of marijuana in certain states only removes the state law. So cities or counties in those states MAY have laws preventing usage. And this is to say nothing of the federal law. It is illegal within the united states to use Marijuana. All of it. Because of the federal law. That said, the FBI is probably unlikely to visit you to find out if you're using it. So that mainly only affects dealers and distributors.
